<a href="#how_to" class="text-4xl" id="how_to"># How To</a>
<hr class="h-1 mx-auto my-4 bg-gray-700 border-0 rounded md:my-10"/>
<p class="text-lg mt-10">
    @if/@elseif/@else operates in the same spirit as Vue's v-if/v-elseif/v-else: a mechanism to conditional render
    markup.
</p>

<div style="background-color: #1d2538;"
     class="mt-10 overflow-x-scroll max-w-sm sm:max-w-7xl border-2 border-gray-800 rounded-lg shadow-xl drop-shadow-lg">
            <pre>
                <code class="language-html -mb-10 -mt-3">
&lt;div ignite="conditional"&gt;
    &lt;div @if="show">
        &lt;span @text="message"&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;/div>
    &lt;div @else>
        No hello world for you
    &lt;/div>
&lt;/div&gt;

&lt;script&gt;
    function conditional() {
        return {
            show: true,
            message: 'hello world',
        }
    }
&lt;/script&gt;
                </code>
            </pre>
</div>
<div class="my-10 text-lg">
    The code above will result in the following (with further styling added, a couple name changes, and a button):
</div>

<div ignite="conditional">
    <div @if="show">
        <span @text="message"></span>
    </div>
    <div @else>
        No hello world for you
    </div>
    <button
            @click="toggleShow"
            class="mt-3 flex-none rounded-md bg-stone-500 px-3.5 py-2.5 text-sm font-semibold text-white shadow-sm hover:bg-stone-400 focus-visible:outline focus-visible:outline-2 focus-visible:outline-offset-2 focus-visible:outline-stone-500"
    >
        Toggle Show
    </button>
</div>

<script nonce="{{@cspNonce}}">
    function conditional() {
        return {
            show: true,
            message: 'hello world',
            toggleShow() {
                this.show = !this.show;
            }
        }
    }
</script>